{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642967"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:47:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:47:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17976"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17976"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.78,0.02,0.15,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10690"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73073"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10690"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17976"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58544"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"11220"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24893"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24896"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73073"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EXenobiotic metabolism refers to the process by which foreign compounds, such as drugs and toxins, are metabolised in the body. This process is essential for the detoxification and elimination of these compounds.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following organs is primarily responsible for the metabolism of food-borne products in xenobiotic metabolism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Liver","Lungs","Stomach","Gall bladder","Pancreas"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary organ responsible for xenobiotic metabolism, including the metabolism of food-borne products. It contains a variety of enzymes, such as cytochrome P450 enzymes, that modify and break down foreign compounds to facilitate their excretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELungs\u003C/strong\u003E - While the lungs can metabolise some inhaled substances, they are not the primary site for xenobiotic metabolism\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGall bladder\u003C/strong\u003E - The gall bladder stores bile but does not play a direct role in xenobiotic metabolism\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStomach\u003C/strong\u003E - The stomach is involved in digestion but not in the metabolism of xenobiotics\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreas\u003C/strong\u003E - The pancreas produces digestive enzymes but is not involved in xenobiotic metabolism\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The liver is the primary organ responsible for xenobiotic metabolism, including the metabolism of food-borne products.","Xenobiotic metabolism involves the modification and breakdown of foreign compounds, such as drugs and toxins, to facilitate their excretion from the body.","The liver contains enzymes that are crucial for the detoxification and metabolism of xenobiotics."],"references":["Gilbert-Barness, E., Barness, L. A., \u0026 Farrell, P. M. (Eds.). (2017). Metabolic diseases: foundations of clinical management, genetics, and pathology. IOS Press.","Lanham-New, S. A., Macdonald, I. A., \u0026 Roche, H. M. (Eds.). (2011). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons.","Roche, H. M., Macdonald, I. A., Schols, A. M., \u0026 Lanham-New, S. A. (Eds.). (2024). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons.","Omiecinski CJ, Vanden Heuvel JP, Perdew GH, Peters JM. Xenobiotic metabolism, disposition, and regulation by receptors: from biochemical phenomenon to predictors of major toxicities. Toxicol Sci. 2011 Mar;120 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):S49-75. doi: 10.1093/toxsci/kfq338. Epub 2010 Nov 8. PMID: 21059794; PMCID: PMC3145385."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58544"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17976"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58544"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T00:47:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T00:48:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10690"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73073"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCo